Philippine Stocks: Cebu Air, Lopez, Manila Electric, Philex

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-03-01T04:40:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-01/philippine-stocks-cebu-air-lopez-manila-electric-philex.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the noon close in Manila.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 0.5 percent to
3,784.23. The gauge climbed for a third day, the longest winning
streak since a four-day advance ending on Jan. 17.  Metals producers:  Philex Mining Corp . (PX PM), the nation’s
biggest miner, gained 4.1 percent to 14.30 pesos, the steepest
rise since Dec. 6 after the price of gold gained for a third day
and headed for the highest close in two months.  Atlas
Consolidated Mining & Development  Corp. (AT PM) rose 3.1 percent
to 15.56 pesos, the sharpest gain since Feb. 2.  Gold for immediate delivery increased 0.1 percent to
$1,412.80 an ounce, set for the highest close since Jan. 3.    Cebu Air Inc . (CEB PM), the  Philippines ’ biggest budget
carrier, jumped 10 percent to 90.20 pesos, the most since the
stock began trading in October after its board approved a share
buyback program. The company said it will spend as much as 2
billion pesos ($46 million) to buy back shares.    Lopez Holdings Corp . (LPZ PM), which has investments in
energy and media, advanced 2.3 percent to 4.90 pesos, the
highest since Jan. 27 after President Salvador Tirona said the
company plans to start declaring dividends. Separately, the
stock was rated “buy” with a 12-month price estimate of 6.51
pesos a share in initial coverage by ATR KimEng Securities Inc.    Manila Electric Co . (MER PM), the largest Philippine power
retailer, gained 1.3 percent to 234 pesos, rebounding from a 2.9
percent loss yesterday. The utility may spend $2 billion to $2.3
billion to build an estimated 1,500 megawatts of power
generating capacity from 2012 to 2016, Chief Operating Officer
Oscar Reyes said. The utility said profit rose to 9.7 billion
pesos last year from 6 billion pesos in 2009.    Metro Pacific Investments Corp . (MPI PM), which has
investments in energy, water and toll roads, advanced 2 percent
to 3.50 pesos, the most since Feb. 2. The company plans to bid
for toll roads, railways and ports the government will offer to
investors, Chairman Manuel Pangilinan said.    MRC Allied Inc . (MRC PM) advanced 2.7 percent to 76
centavos, the steepest gain since Jan. 25. The company said in a
stock exchange filing that it will buy two more mining assets by
end-June and that it’s in talks with investors for possible
ventures.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
 isayson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
